default&#xa0;
defaultAre current safety measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved? default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?default&#xa0;
default8
default              
defaultT
defaulthere is a comprehensive
default approach to improving safety at level crossings, includ
defaulting
default a programme of level crossing closures and improvements, risk assessments using the 
defaultAll Level Crossing Risk Model (ALCRM)
default model, thorough accident investigations and an extensive research and deve
defaultlopment programme.
default 
default&#xa0;
default9
default              
defaultHowever, given that level crossings are places where roads and road users cross the railway, they inevitably remain high risk infrastructure. 
defaultT
defaulthe most effective way to reduce accidents, deaths and injuries at level crossings is to 
defaultclose the crossings
default if
default possible
default, 
defaultwhich
default is Network Rail’s policy. 
defaultThey have 
defaultclosed 700 level crossings across Britain 
default(about 
default10
default%
default of the total
default)
default since 2009 as part of 
defaulttheir
default £130m national level crossing investment programme.
default 
defaultHowever, it is 
defaultnot 
defaultpossible to 
defaultcl
defaultose all crossings without a huge investment to provide alternatives, such as tunnels, bridges or road diversions
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default10
default              
defaultThe next most effective approach 
defaultis
default to design level crossings that depend as little as possible on road users behaving safely
default, 
defaultbecause crossings which depend on the behaviour of road users 
defaulthave the highest accident risks.
default 
defaultAn example of this approach is converting 
defaultautomatic half-barrier crossings to automatic full-barrier crossings with obstacle detection
default, so that a train is not cl
defaulteared to pass the crossing unless it 
defaultis 
defaultclear.
default 
default&#xa0;
default11
default              
defaultGiven the dominance of road user misuse as the cause of level crossing accidents, close co-operation between the railway sector and highway authorities and the police is essential.
default It would also be useful
default if there were fewer different types of level crossings as this would help the public to understand how they should be used.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1
default2
default              
defaultThe level and type
default of information differs significantly by level crossing type and 
defaultsometimes 
defaultwithin a single type of level crossing. 
defaultIn r
defaultoad user surveys and trials
default all 
defaultrespondents underst
defaultood the ‘stop’ signals 
defaultbut responses to ‘amber’ and ‘not illuminated’ varied.
default 
defaultParticipants identified level crossing advance warning signs, but did not associat
defaulte the different signs and signals with different types of level crossing. Comprehension of the St Andrew’s cross was particularly poor.
default&#xa0;
default1
default3
default              
defaultAwareness of the possibility of second trains was low
default, with participants 
defaultexpect
defaulting
default the barrier to rise immediately after the first train.
default 
defaultIn video scenarios, a
