defaultHow should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail budget?default&#xa0;
defaultIs Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety defaultat level crossings?default&#xa0;
default1
default8
default              
defaultL
defaultevel crossings represent a growing proportion of the 
defaultall railway deaths
default. According to the review (mentioned above)
default, by 
default2009 
defaultdeaths at level crossings 
defaultrepre
defaultsented 46% of all railway 
defaultfatal
defaultities
default (excluding trespassers and suicides) – 
defaultit was 11% in 1946 - 1950
default.
default 
defaultTherefore, improving safety at level crossings should be one of the top safety priorities for the rail budget.
default&#xa0;
default1
default9
default              
defaultGiven the fact that road users are the main cause of most level crossing accidents, there is a case for road 
defaultbudgets being used to help fund safety improvements at level crossings. The difficulty is that level crossing crashes and casualties are a very small proportion of overall road accidents and casualties (even though they are a major proportion of railway ac
defaultcidents and casualties). Therefore, it is natural tha
defaultt road safety budgets are focus
defaulted on the main road safety issues. 
default&#xa0;
default20
default              
defaultHowever, t
defaulthe railways, highway authorities, police and HSE need to work closely together to ensure a consistent and integrated appro
defaultach to level crossing safety, b
defaulto
defaultth in terms of national policy and local policy at level crossing sites.
default 
defaultNow that some 
defaultresponsibility for public health 
defaulthas been
default transferred to local authorities, 
defaultin England, t
defaulthe
defaultre 
defaultshould 
defaultalso be 
defaultopportunities for 
defaultcloser working with public health 
defaultservices.
