default&#xa0;defaultIs Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?default&#xa0;
default21
default              
defaultMis
defaultuse
default of level crossings by drivers should be treated as a serious criminal off
defaultence
default because t
defaulthe potential 
defaultto cause a catastrophic accident, resulting in multiple fatalities
default,
default is clearly high. A collision between a train and a car at a level crossing in 2004 caus
defaulted 7 deaths. The law and the penalties should reflect this level of risk.
default R
defaultoSPA 
defaultbelieves
default that 
defaultcurrent 
defaultroad traffic offences should continue to regulate the conduct of drivers at level crossings
default that cross roads
default; i
defaultt seems unnecessary to create new offences
default.
default&#xa0;
default22
default              
defaultHowever, 
defaultthere is a case for new offences related to pedestrian behaviour at level crossings
default because r
defaultoad traffic offences do not, in general, regulate the conduct of pedestrians. 
defaultIn 2012/1
default3, 4
default pedestrians were killed at level crossings
default, 302 were involved in near misses with trains at level crossings and 1,822 incidents of pedestrian misuse of level crossings were reported. 
defaultThe RSSB has 
defaultestimated
default that the risk of death or serious injury to pedestrians makes up 77% of the total risk to th
defaultose crossing the railway at level crossings
default. A
default large proportion of this risk occurs at footpath crossings.
default&#xa0;
default2
default3
default              
defaultTherefore, 
defaultRoSPA believes that there is a case for 
defaultnew offences that would apply to pedestrians who deliberately mis-use level crossing. However,
default it 
defaultmust be made 
defaultclear 
defaultat the crossings 
defaultwhen and how 
defaultpedestrians 
defaultshould cross
default so that 
defaultthey 
defaultdo not 
defaultface charges for reasonable mistakes.
default&#xa0;
default2
default4
default              
defaultIt is important that laws and penalties act as a deterrent, which means that they have to be widely known, 
defaultand 
defaultthere
default must also be a perception that those who breach the laws are likely to be detected and prosecuted.
